Organization: CEBAF
Date: Tue, 11 Oct 1994 13:10:04 GMT

Hi!  I'm looking for free advice, as usual ..  are any engineers
from Intel listening?  My question involves thermal characteristics
and reliability of Intel 0.6-micron CPUs.

I poked into a friend's new DX4, and found something that disturbed me.
When running DOS or 1.0.x Linux, the chip runs hot enough to fry eggs
(this is with a heat sink, and a fan blowing across it, although not
a direct-mounted fan).  When running recent 1.1.x Linux, which HLTs
the CPU when it has nothing better to do, the CPU is basically cold
most of the time.

In real life use, the CPU will end up thermal cycling quite a few
times per day - every recompile, every Mosaic start, every page
preview is going to load down the processor and build up some heat.

Question 1: Does the P-90 have the same qualitative behavior?
 (HLT puts it in a mode that dissipates negligible power)

Question 2: Are these 0.6-micron chips (and their wire bonds) built to
 stand 10^5 thermal cycles?  (100 cycles per day for three years - actual
 pattern will probably be fractal/chaotic in nature)

Question 3: Are these chips (and their wire bonds) built to take the small
 but continual vibration from fans mounted directly on the heat sink?

Question 4: I have heard Intel's chips carry a lifetime warrantee.
 Does this apply to the conditions described in my questions 2 and 3?

Question 5: How much power should these chips actually dissipate?
 (I thought the DX4/100 was supposed to be low-power compared with the
 older DX2/66 which has larger geometry and 5V supply)

I am about to coordinate purchases of a few mid-high end PC's,
with either 486DX4/100's or P-90s.  We can't afford to end up
with unreliable systems.

E-mail or newsgroup discussion/answers OK.  I will summarize and post
anything I learn off-group.

            - Larry Doolittle   doolittle@cebaf.gov


