Sam Brown (rigor@crl.com) wrote:
: really the p5-90 i have is rock solid, we dont even use power management, 
: the dx-4-100 and p5-90 are designed to have a direct-mount heatsink/fan 
: combo on them for best cooling, a peltier junction would be your best bet 
: if you are rreally paranoid, it kept my old dx-2-50 running at 66mghz 
: around 80 degress all summer long, on at full speed all the time.

Does this mean the the p5-90 doesn't go low power when it hits a "HLT"
instruction?  Keeping the chip warmed up all the time is different
(and from a reliability point of view not necessarily better or worse)
than only warming it up under heavy load.

If, as you say, "the dx-4-100 and p5-90 are designed to have a direct-mount
heatsink/fan combo on them for best cooling", does that mean Intel supports
their use and isn't worried about vibration?

Unlike many people, I have a *choice* which way to run.  I can patch
my kernel (Linux) to loop instead of HLT when Idle.  The laptop users
really like the HLT mode.  The EPA really likes the HLT mode.  My
question is, am I unnecessarily risking a $900 chip when I do this
on a desktop P-90?

